Before C++17 we needed to mark a variable as `extern` to share it among different translation units. We would need to provide an explicit definition of the variable in one translation unit in this case:

```
// common.h
extern const std::vector&lt;int&gt; g_numbers;


// a.cpp
#include &quot;common.h&quot;

const std::vector&lt;int&gt; g_numbers = { 1, 2, 3 };

void a() { /* use g_numbers */ }


// b.cpp
#include &quot;common.h&quot;

void b() { /* use g_numbers */ }
```

But since C++17 we can declare the variable `inline`, and the linker will handle the definition of the variable for us:

```
// common.h
inline const std::vector&lt;int&gt; g_numbers = { 1, 2, 3 };


// a.cpp
#include &quot;common.h&quot;

void a() { /* use g_numbers */ }


// b.cpp
#include &quot;common.h&quot;

void b() { /* use g_numbers */ }
```

Given the fact this is a more convenient and straight-forward way to define a shared variable, I wonder is there still a place for `extern` variables in C++17?

